\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]

% Pentagon vertices
\node (v1) at (0,0) {};
\node (v2) at (1,1) {};
\node (v3) at (2,0) {};
\node (v4) at (1,-1) {};
\node (v5) at (0,0) {};

% Draw the pentagon
\draw (v1) -- (v2) -- (v3) -- (v4) -- (v5);

% Triangulation of the pentagon
\draw (v1) -- (v2);
\draw (v2) -- (v3);
\draw (v3) -- (v4);
\draw (v4) -- (v1);

% Snake graph for the longest arc γ
\node (s) at (3,0) {s};
\node (t) at (4,0) {t};

\draw[dashed] (v2) -- (s);
\draw[dashed] (v3) -- (t);

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

This code will produce a diagram with:
1. A pentagon drawn as a closed shape.
2. The pentagon triangulated by drawing lines between its vertices.
3. A dashed line from vertex \(v_2\) to node \(s\) and from vertex \(v_3\) to node \(t\), representing the snake graph for the longest arc \(\gamma\).

You can compile this LaTeX code using a LaTeX editor to see the resulting diagram.

